<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-146-184  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 146 184.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  March 1989 v6 n2 p95(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Effective legal remedies for attacks are few. (computer virusesand other attacks on computer systems and networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gemignani, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Legal methods intended to prevent attacks on computer systems andnetworks similar to the computer virus that infected the Internetnetwork in Nov 1988 suffer from limited effectiveness.andP;  Title 18,Section 1030 of the US Criminal Code would seem to protectInternet from such attacks, but legal questions surround whatexactly is unauthorized access and what the penalty should be forunintentional damage to data.andP;  Many states have enacted lawsprotecting computers and the data they store, but the laws varywidely from state to state.andP;  It is also difficult to establish theintention of the accused in such cases.andP;  Civil law probably doesnot provide an alternative to criminal law because of the highcost of such prosecution and the low awards, and because provingloss is difficult.andP;  Proving who is responsible for the virus orworm brings many privacy issues into question as well.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LegislationComputer VirusesLegal IssuesData SecurityAnalysisInternet (Computer network)Issues-Society.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>